---
alwaysApply: true
---
# Cursor Rules: Department Engineering Standards

rules:
  - id: department.core.innovation_structure
    description: |
      Prioritize innovative solutions that maintain architectural integrity.
      Design with modularity, extensibility, and maintainability in mind.
      Evaluate all changes for systemic impact on the cognitive framework.
      Prefer elegant, well-structured solutions over expedient quick fixes.
    severity: error

  - id: department.core.industry_quality
    description: |
      Code must be production-ready and fully functional at all times.
      Follow established patterns and best practices in cognitive systems engineering.
      Code must rigorously meet standards required for review at a top-tier organization.
    severity: error

  - id: department.code.production_quality
    description: |
      No placeholder code, TODOs, or incomplete implementations permitted.
      All functions must handle edge cases and error conditions explicitly.
      Code must be performant, maintainable, and secure.
      Type hints, docstrings, and comprehensive error handling are mandatory.
    severity: error

  - id: department.core.fallback_philosophy
    description: |
      Only use fallbacks when they represent the correct architectural solution.
      Never use fallbacks to avoid fixing root causes or underlying issues.
      If a fallback is required, document and justify its use with architectural reasoning.
      Always address root causes directly rather than masking them.
    severity: error

  - id: department.responsibilities.brain_module_development
    description: |
      Follow established module architecture when designing cognitive modules.
      Ensure seamless integration with the brain framework and consistency with BaseBrainModule.
      Implement robust operation dispatch, input validation, and error handling.
    severity: error

  - id: department.responsibilities.proactive_enhancement
    description: |
      Proactively identify and address gaps in architecture, performance, or functionality.
      Implement enhancements with consideration for both immediate needs and long-term evolution.
    severity: warning

  - id: department.responsibilities.safety_frameworks
    description: |
      Design and implement robust, testable, and well-documented safety mechanisms.
      Consider edge cases, adversarial scenarios, and integrate safety checks at the right architectural layer.
    severity: error

  - id: department.responsibilities.ui_ux
    description: |
      UI components must be intuitive, accessible, and consistent with the cognitive architecture.
      Always maintain established design patterns and serve both technical and end users.
    severity: warning

  - id: department.responsibilities.system_enhancement
    description: |
      Continuously improve performance, reliability, and maintainability.
      Refactor for clarity and efficiency, reduce technical debt, and enhance observability and debugging.
    severity: warning

  - id: department.quality.functionality
    description: |
      Code must be fully functional and executable; no stubbed or incomplete methods.
      Explicitly handle all edge cases.
      Error messages must be clear and actionable.
    severity: error

  - id: department.quality.testing_validation
    description: |
      Perform comprehensive parameter validation and error handling.
      Test all edge cases and failure scenarios.
      Ensure correctness in isolation and integration.
    severity: error

  - id: department.quality.documentation
    description: |
      Write complete docstrings for all public APIs, and document design decisions.
      Explain complex logic thoroughly, with inline comments as needed.
    severity: error

  - id: department.quality.organization
    description: |
      Follow project structure and naming conventions.
      Keep code modular, cohesive, and maintain clear separation of concerns.
      Minimize coupling between components.
    severity: error

  - id: department.problem_solving.process
    description: |
      1. Fully understand the problem and context before proposing solutions.
      2. Design the architecture before writing code.
      3. Always fix the root cause, never mask problems.
      4. Evaluate system-wide impact of all changes.
      5. Refine solutions based on testing and feedback.
    severity: error

  - id: department.communication
    description: |
      Communicate with precision and technical clarity.
      Reference patterns and design principles.
      Explain rationale behind decisions; address trade-offs and constraints directly.
    severity: warning

  - id: department.prohibited_practices
    description: |
      Prohibited:
        - Using fallbacks to avoid fixing real issues
        - Leaving incomplete or placeholder code
        - Ignoring error conditions or edge cases
        - Writing code that "works for now" without proper structure
        - Making unconsidered changes with system-wide impact
        - Skipping documentation or type hints
        - Implementing quick fixes that incur technical debt
    severity: error

  - id: department.required_practices
    description: |
      Required:
        - Design with architecture and structure in mind
        - Implement functional, production-ready code
        - Handle all error conditions explicitly
        - Write comprehensive documentation
        - Consider system-wide implications
        - Follow patterns and conventions meticulously
        - Fix root causes rather than symptoms
        - Test thoroughly and validate all assumptions
    severity: error

  - id: department.standards.integration
    description: |
      These department rules must be applied together with:
        - Python standards (PEP 8, modern typing)
        - Module architecture standards (BaseBrainModule patterns)
        - Internal/external publication style guidelines
      Compliance with all relevant standards is required for code acceptance.
    severity: error
